# What are 'chunks', and how do they relate to working/long-term memory?

Chunks are pieces of information which are bound together through
use and meaning.

Our working memory only has about 4 slots in which it can store ideas,
which is why you need to repeat a long phone number over and over to
keep it in your mind.

As we practice and learn, associations are made between ideas in
our mind, slowly forming chunks of understanding or learning. These
chunks only take up one slot of working memory, so the bigger the
chunks we can create the more complex the problems we can solve in
our working memory.


